isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.53) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.24. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [12.99, 14.07]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.39, p = 0.741, 95% CI [-0.89, 0.63]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.48, S.E. = 0.33, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.13, -1.84]; Std. beta = -0.58, 95% CI [-0.74, -0.43])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.96, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.93, -1.99]; Std. beta = -0.70, 95% CI [-0.93, -0.47])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
